<mjml>
  <mj-head>
    <mj-style> h2,img,p { margin:0; } td{ padding-top:0 !important; } p {margin-bottom: 10px;}</mj-style>
    <!-- <mj-font name="Roboto" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Roboto" /> -->
    <mj-font name="Roboto+Serif" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto+Serif:ital,opsz,wght@0,8..144,100..900;1,8..144,100..900&display=swap" />
  </mj-head>
  <mj-body background-color="#f0f1f3">


    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
    
    <!-- Logo Header -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-spacer height="10px" />
      <mj-column padding="10px 12px 10px 12px" width="100%">
        <mj-spacer height="16px" />
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" css-class="light_img" width="150px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/logo-gray.png" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" alt="" />
        
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 0px" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 2px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="
              font-size: 16px;
              line-height: 1.5;
            ">Every successful company has a turning point—a risk that paid off, a product that redefined an industry, or a decision that changed everything. However, not every story is one of triumph; some of the most valuable lessons come from the failures and missteps that shaped the business landscape.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 0px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    
    <mj-spacer height="10px"></mj-spacer>

    <!-- Bussiness history -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_fsection" background-color="#ffffff" css-class="mj_fsection">
      <mj-column background-color="#ffffff" width="100%">
        <mj-text padding="2px 12px 0px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="white">
          <h2 style="
          padding-top:14px;
          color:#8C3321;
            text-align: left;
            border-bottom:2px solid #8C3321;
              font-size: 26px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              padding-bottom:8px;
            ">The Tajmahal Casino: Trumped by a whale</h2> 
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">An Atlantic City showdown</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          What happens when one of the world’s top gamblers takes on a casino mogul who despises losing, especially when that mogul happens to be Donald Trump? Meet Akio Kashiwagi, known in gambling circles as “The Warrior,” a world-class baccarat player and successful Japanese real estate tycoon with rumored ties to the Yakuza. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/trump-akio-kashiwagi-casino-showdown-1990-millions-lost.png" alt="In 1990, Trump and Akio Kasiwagi had an epic and remarkably personal showdown in which millions of dollars changed hands in days" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>In 1990, Trump and Akio Kasiwagi had an epic and remarkably personal showdown in which a lot of money changed hands in a few days. Credits: News UK</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In the late 1980s and early ’90s, Trump had just opened three casinos in Atlantic City: the Trump Plaza (1984), Trump Castle (1985), and his crown jewel, the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-03-05-2025-tajmahal-casino?source=website" target="_blank">Trump Taj Mahal</a> in 1990. Unseemly dubbed “the eighth wonder of the world,” the casino was valued at over $1B and came with a daily credit burden of nearly $3M in interest payments. Trump’s casino empire was hemorrhaging money. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          So, in classic Trumpian fashion, he staged a spectacle. He planned to invite Akio Kashiwagi, one of the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-03-05-2025-biggest-gambling-whale-in-the-world?source=website" target="_blank">biggest gambling whales in the world</a>, to his casino to gain big. Kashiwagi had previously walked away with $20M from Australia’s Diamond Beach Casino, nearly bankrupting it, and on other occasions lost money at Steve Wynn’s Mirage in Las Vegas. He was known for playing marathon sessions, betting $200,000 per hand, sometimes gambling for over 80 hours straight.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>
    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
  </mj-body>
</mjml>